structure:Code.common:Name: Hourly
structure:Code.common:Description: To be used for data collected or disseminated every hour.

structure:Code.common:Name: Daily
structure:Code.common:Description: To be used for data collected or disseminated every day.

structure:Code.common:Name: Minutely
structure:Code.common:Description: While N denotes "minutely", usually, there may be no observations every minute (for several series the frequency is usually "irregular" within a day/days). And though observations may be sparse (not collected or disseminated every minute), missing values do not need to be given for the minutes when no observations exist: in any case the time stamp determines when an observation is observed.

structure:Code.common:Name: Daily or businessweek
structure:Code.common:Description: Similar to "daily", however there are no observations for Saturdays and Sundays (so, neither "missing values" nor "numeric values" should be provided for Saturday and Sunday). This treatment ("business") is one way to deal with such cases, but it is not the only option. Such a time series could alternatively be considered daily ("D"), thus, with missing values in the weekend.

structure:Code.common:Name: Weekly
structure:Code.common:Description: To be used for data collected or disseminated every week.

structure:Concept.common:Name: Unit of measure
structure:Concept.common:Description: The unit in which the data values are measured.

common:Annotation.common:AnnotationText: e.g. a unit multiplier of 3 would mean that the observation repsesents thousands.

structure:Concept.common:Name: Unit multiplier
structure:Concept.common:Description: Quantity the data is recorded in.

structure:Concept.common:Name: Observation status
structure:Concept.common:Description: Information on the quality of a value or an unusual or missing value.

structure:Concept.common:Name: Observation Comment
structure:Concept.common:Description: This attribute is typically a catch all for free text annoations from the information warehouse.

structure:Concept.common:Name: Reference Base Period
structure:Concept.common:Description: The period at which the index is set as 100.0.

common:Annotation.common:AnnotationText: The measurement represented by each observation corresponds to a specific point in time (e.g. a single day) or a period (e.g. a month, a fiscal year, or a calendar year). This is used as a time stamp and is of particular importance for time series data. In cases where the actual time period of the data differs from the target reference period, "time period" refers to the actual period.

structure:Concept.common:Name: Time period
structure:Concept.common:Description: The period of time or point in time to which the measured observation refers.

common:Annotation.common:AnnotationText: The "observation value" is the field which holds the data.

structure:Concept.common:Name: Observation value
structure:Concept.common:Description: The value of a particular variable at a particular period.

structure:Concept.common:Name: Frequency
structure:Concept.common:Description: The rate at which data is collated.

structure:Concept.common:Name: Measure
structure:Concept.common:Description: Statistical concepts for which data is provided.

structure:Concept.common:Name: Ajustment Type
structure:Concept.common:Description: The statistical method applied to time series data.
